1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Be3 { The Alapin Gambit. White develops a piece and dares Black to take e4. Across roughly 284,000 Lichess games (blitz, rapid and classical) White scores 52 percent here, and the positions are far easier to play for White: every plan is the same attacking plan. } 3... dxe4 { Taken in 61 percent of games - 77 percent at 2200+. The declines 3...Nf6, 3...c5, 3...c6 and 3...Nc6 are Chapters 7-10. } 4. Nd2 { Stockfish's top choice and more flexible than the immediate 4.f3: the knight is headed for f3, c4 or e5, and White keeps every option of regaining e4 or gambitting it properly. } 4... Nf6 { Natural development, 66 percent of games. The pawn-clinging 4...f5 is Chapter 6. } 5. f3 { The gambit proper. White offers a second pawn to open the f-file; after the recapture every white piece flows toward the black king. Stockfish holds Black's edge to -0.8 with perfect play, but humans never manage it: White scores 52-53 percent at every band from 1400 to 2500. } 5... exf3 { 80 percent accept. The engine's stubborn 5...Nd5 decline is Chapter 5. } 6. Ngxf3 { The right recapture - the d2-knight keeps its routes to c4, e5 and e4. } 6... Be7 { The most popular setup, 32 percent. 6...Bd6 is Chapter 2; the rest of Black's sixth moves are Chapters 3 and 4. } 7. Bd3 { Aimed at h7. From here the attack plays itself: O-O, Qe1-h4, Ne5, Bg5, rooks to the f-file. } 7... O-O 8. O-O b6 { 39 percent and the main branch. } 9. Qe1 { The signature regrouping: the queen swings to h4 and every later sacrifice on the kingside has backup. White already scores 57 percent. } 9... Bb7 { Universal (90 percent of games at every band) - and the moment the gambit pawn is repaid in full: Stockfish now says +0.1 for White, and the practical score rises to 58 percent. } 10. Qh4 Nbd7 { The main defensive setup. } 11. Ne5 { The clamp on f7 and g6. Engine: balanced. Practice: Black must produce only-moves while White's hands play themselves. } 11... g6 { The most common defence (40 percent of games) and the losing one: Stockfish jumps to +1.9. } 12. Bg5 { +2.1. The e7-bishop is the lone defender of the dark squares, so White trades it or wins it. } 12... Nxe5 13. dxe5 Nd5 14. Ne4 { The d2-knight has been an attacker all game; now it heads for f6 or d6. } 14... Bxg5 15. Nxg5 h5 16. Be4 { Total domination for the pawn: +2.5, 80 percent practical score. } 16... Qe7 17. Rf3 { The lift - Rh3 or Rf6 next, and the d5-knight is pinned to the b7-bishop's defence. } 17... Rad8 18. c4 { +2.5 and the knight must abandon the blockade. This single line is the heart of the course: Bd3, Qe1-h4, Ne5, Bg5 - the same attack, game after game, at every level. } *

