1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Be3 { The Alapin Gambit. White develops a piece and dares Black to take e4. Across roughly 284,000 Lichess games (blitz, rapid and classical) White scores 52 percent here, and the positions are far easier to play for White: every plan is the same attacking plan. } 3... dxe4 { Taken in 61 percent of games - 77 percent at 2200+. The declines 3...Nf6, 3...c5, 3...c6 and 3...Nc6 are Chapters 7-10. } 4. Nd2 { Stockfish's top choice and more flexible than the immediate 4.f3: the knight is headed for f3, c4 or e5, and White keeps every option of regaining e4 or gambitting it properly. } 4... Nf6 { Natural development, 66 percent of games. The pawn-clinging 4...f5 is Chapter 6. } 5. f3 { The gambit proper. White offers a second pawn to open the f-file; after the recapture every white piece flows toward the black king. Stockfish holds Black's edge to -0.8 with perfect play, but humans never manage it: White scores 52-53 percent at every band from 1400 to 2500. } 5... exf3 { 80 percent accept. The engine's stubborn 5...Nd5 decline is Chapter 5. } 6. Ngxf3 { The right recapture - the d2-knight keeps its routes to c4, e5 and e4. } 6... Be7 { The most popular setup, 32 percent. 6...Bd6 is Chapter 2; the rest of Black's sixth moves are Chapters 3 and 4. } 7. Bd3 { Aimed at h7. From here the attack plays itself: O-O, Qe1-h4, Ne5, Bg5, rooks to the f-file. } 7... O-O 8. O-O Nbd7 9. Nc4 { Rerouting: the knight eyes e5 and d6. After 9...c5 10.c3 White keeps the grip; engine near -1.0, practical score 51 percent and the easier game. } *

