1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Be3 dxe4 4. Nd2 Nf6 5. f3 exf3 6. Ngxf3 Bd6 { Second most popular, 20 percent: more active than 6...Be7, but the bishop walks away from the kingside dark squares - and unlike the e7-bishop it can never come back to f6 or g5 to bail the king out. The punishments below all flow from that single fact. } 7. Bd3 O-O 8. Qe2 { Against the d6-setup the queen prefers e2: White keeps the long-castling option and avoids committing the king where the d6-bishop points. } 8... Nbd7 9. O-O-O { The h-pawn becomes a battering ram and every tempo counts double. } 9... c5 10. Rhf1 { Full mobilisation first: from here White scores 71 percent. Sacrifices on f6 and f7 and the g4-g5 push are all in the air, and Black's queenside counterplay is a move too slow. } *

