1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Be3 Nf6 { The most popular decline (19 percent) - and already an error worth +0.7: Black walks into a French Advance where Be3, normally a luxury White cannot afford so early, is on the board for free. } 4. e5 Nfd7 5. f4 { The Advance French, improved: Be3 already overprotects d4, so Black's entire ...Qb6 counterplay system - the spine of normal French theory - misfires. } 5... c5 6. c3 Nc6 7. Nf3 Qb6 { The standard recipe against the Advance: pressure d4 and b2. Here it is simply worse than usual - White's eval is +1.0 and climbs from here. } 8. Qd2 cxd4 9. cxd4 Bb4 { The pin against d2 - the engine's main try. } 10. Nc3 O-O 11. Bd3 f6 { The thematic strike at e5 - and here it backfires spectacularly. } 12. O-O fxe5 { Two-thirds of players release the tension at once, and it is the decisive mistake. } 13. fxe5 { +4.1. The f-file belongs to White (compare Chapter 1!), e6 hangs in many lines, and Ng5 plus Bxh7 motifs are everywhere. Everything Black wanted from ...f6 went to White instead. } *

