1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Be3 c5 { The French reflex, 6 percent of games - already imprecise (+0.9), and the single richest source of blunders in the entire opening. } 4. dxc5 { The point: the e3-bishop guards c5, a fact Black misses with astonishing frequency at every level. } 4... Qa5+ { The most cunning try (26 percent): check first, intending to win c5 next move. } 5. Nc3 { Block with development, and watch what happens to the pawn-grabbers. } 5... Bxc5 { The most instructive statistic in the course: 92 percent of all players - 71 percent even at 2200+ - take the bishop, certain that the a5-queen protects it. } 6. Bb5+ { The move this chapter exists to teach. The check lands ON THE FIFTH RANK: the b5-bishop physically severs the a5-queen's defence of c5, so the c5-bishop is suddenly loose - and ...Qxc5 is illegal as long as b5 blocks the rank. } 6... Bd7 { The best defence: offer to trade the checking bishop. } 7. Bxc5 { Winning eval (+3.4) - but precision matters here, and the v1 course got this wrong: this does NOT win a piece by force. } 7... Bxb5 { Black regains the piece - material will be level again. } 8. Qd4 { The follow-up that keeps everything: hitting g7 and centralising. } 8... Nf6 9. exd5 { +3.4 with level material: the d5-passer, the monster on c5, the wrecked black kingside and the stranded king are together worth a piece - which is different from being one up. (The clean piece only comes after 6...Nc6.) White converts these positions at 61 percent even at club level, and with this chapter learned it should be far more. } *

